As improved treatments for congenital heart disease (CHD) have increased life 
expectancy, neurodevelopmental impairments have been observed in many survivors. 
These impairments include developmental delays, difficulty in school, and 
challenges living independently. Understanding the causes of these impairments 
and minimizing their impact are important goals to allow survivors to have the 
best possible quality of life.

